A well polished and enjoyable game. Smooth difficulty curve, well designed environments, cute characters, and great music are just a few of the things that make this a worthwhile purchase.   If you liked collectable based games, like Banjo-Kazooie or Mario 64, there's a good chance you'll like this. The stars hidden throughout the level give reason to replay levels and explore further. Even on replay, the levels seldom feel repetitive.  The controls could be better and there are times when you may be fighting the camera angle and invisible joystick to get Suzy to move or jump where you want. Not having a visible joystick on the screen makes the UI less distracting, but it can make it difficult to define the limits of the control you have over Suzy. For me, I would find my left thumb sliding over the middle and right side of the screen.  There could be more consistency in the use of directional shadows. When the directional 'high noon' shadows are in effect, knowing what Suzy is over is a lot easier. When there are no shadows, it can be difficult to discern her position, particularly over enemies, etc.  Even so, I readily endorse this game.

Very much a 3d Mario inspired game. Disappointed there is effectively one boss with a few different strategies. Also falls short in any innovation, nor does it have the charm and variety of a true Mario game. Works for what it is but don't expect greatness. That said this is an enjoyable experience.

This was quite the game, has a lot of levels and challenge but does have some flaws. The graphics are great and everything is climbable. The levels get more and more complicated and is a great difficulty curve. There's a story but not much but still fun. The gameplay changes up each level per world but then becomes a bit of routine for each world, all have a platform level, a go up level, a go down level, a puzzle level, etc. There's bosses at the end of each too but are usually the same in some way, though still challenging. There's also hat power ups but you need to finish the level to keep them or get more. The flaws come in the controls, they don't work quite as well with the challenges. A lot of levels have platforming challenges or are timed in one way or another and when trying to jump from one place to the next it's hard to keep momentum and you'll stop short mid air. That, the inability to get power ups outside of levels and that it's a paid game is why it gets three stars but that's not bad and still recommend buying

game. You need SIXAXIS app less than $5 it will work on non rooted device 
but you must plug the controller in via PS3 USB to phone OTG cable. This 
game is worth the under $5 fo' sheezy! I'm gonna go get cubed now. Peace 
out!
